type Maybe<T> = T | unknown;
type UseValue<T> = {
  value: T;
  isUnknown: boolean;
};
function useValue<T>(): UseValue<T> {
  const value = ((): unknown)() as unknown;
  const isUnknown = true;
  return { value, isUnknown };
}
// Usage:
const value = useValue<string>(); // string | unknown
if (value.isUnknown) {
  // Handle the unknown value case
}
```
In this example, we define a generic type `Maybe<T>` which is a union type containing `T` and `unknown`. We then define a `UseValue<T>` interface with a `value` and `isUnknown` property. In the `useValue` function, we create an `unknown` value and set the `isUnknown` property to `true`.
In the usage case, we can use `useValue` to get an object with the `value` and `isUnknown` properties. We can then check the `isUnknown` property to determine if the value is indeed unknown. If it is, we can handle that case accordingly.
